          "body": "Balak's response to Israel's advance is illuminating: he does not try to fight first. He tries to curse first (22:6). This is the logic of ancient Near Eastern religion — before battle, neutralize the enemy's divine protection. Balak's acknowledgment that 'he whom you bless is blessed and he whom you curse is cursed' (22:6) is actually a backhanded confession of monotheistic reality: he recognizes that Balaam's power is real and that Israel's God is connected to it. The coalition with Midian (22:4, 7) anticipates the deeper apostasy of Numbers 25 when Midianite women will draw Israel into Baal worship at Peor — a strategy that will succeed where cursing fails. Numbers 22 is therefore not a standalone incident; it is act one of a two-part assault on Israel: external curse (ch. 22-24, which fails) and internal seduction (ch. 25, which succeeds temporarily)."
