        "title": "Two embassies and two nights — God's prohibition and Balaam's second request",
        "range": "22:8-21",
        "excerpt": "God said to Balaam, 'Do not go with them; you shall not curse the people, for they are blessed.' ... God came to Balaam at night and said to him, 'If the men have come to call you, rise up and go with them; but only the word which I speak to you shall you do.'",
        "body": "The first nocturnal consultation (22:8-12) is paradigmatically clean: God comes, Balaam reports the commission accurately, God prohibits the mission with a reason — 'they are blessed' (22:12). Balaam rises in the morning and obeys. The first embassy is dismissed. The clarity of this sequence makes the second request (22:19) theologically damning. Balaam has already been told the answer. He has already demonstrated that he knows how to obey — he did it in verse 13. But when a more impressive and more richly rewarded second embassy arrives (22:15), he reopens the question.\n\nThe tell is verse 19: 'Now please, you also stay here tonight, and I will find out what *else* the LORD will speak to me.' The Hebrew *yasaph* ('again,' 'additionally') reveals that Balaam is not seeking clarification — he already has clarity. He is seeking a revised answer. This is precisely what Peter identifies as the 'error of Balaam' — not ignorance but greed that masquerades as conscientiousness (2 Peter 2:15). Calvin notes that Balaam's second consultation is the behavior of a man who 'wished God to be complicit in his covetousness.' He asks again not because God was unclear but because the reward was attractive.\n\nGod's conditional permission in verse 20 has generated significant interpretive discussion. The Reformed reading, represented by John Owen and followed by commentators such as Gordon Wenham (*Numbers*, TOTC), is that God here operates in His permissive will — granting what Balaam's heart is set on while knowing it will result in further correction. God is not changing His mind; He is letting the man go so that the man's own donkey will do what God's word alone could not penetrate. The Arminian reading — that God genuinely revises His directive based on Balaam's persistence — is possible but undercuts the narrative's point: Balaam's going was not God-approved in any disposition-endorsing sense, as verse 22 immediately establishes.\n\nVerse 22 is the chapter's narrative pivot and its sharpest theological paradox: 'God was angry *because he was going*.' The same going God permitted in verse 20, God is angry about in verse 22. This is not contradiction; it is the Bible's realistic portrayal of divine permission and divine approval as distinct categories. What God allows and what God endorses are not the same. The detail that Balaam *saddled his own donkey* (22:21) — rather than having a servant do it — is a marker of personal urgency. Ancient Near Eastern custom made a man's willingness to saddle his own animal a sign of special motivation. Abraham saddled his own donkey in Genesis 22:3 — in obedience to a divine command. Balaam does the same act in response to a human paymaster.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Akh* ('only,' 22:20, 35) — the particle of restriction, commonly translated 'surely' or 'only.' It carries emphatic limiting force: *only* this word, *only* what I tell you. Its verbatim repetition in 22:35 after the donkey episode signals that the confrontation changed nothing about the constraint — only Balaam's awareness of his situation."
